[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 61 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the South-East Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 49 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
------------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 50 879 new cases (54.5% of the global newly reported cases), and 2810 deaths (63.1%) for this 24-hour period. Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 44.8% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil 29.3%, Peru 8.0%, Chile 4.6%, Mexico 4.2%, and Canada 2.4%. The Americas region has surpassed 2 million cases and is maintaining its status as having the highest cumulative case count of the 6 WHO regions, with the European region as the 2nd-highest region.

The European region reported 19 922 new cases (21.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 1222 deaths (27.4%). Russia reported 44.8% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, followed by the UK 17.7%, Turkey 6.9%, Belarus 4.9%, Italy 3.4%, and Spain 3.3%.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 11 992 new cases (12.8% of the global newly reported cases) and 138 deaths (3.1%). Saudi Arabia reported 22.8% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Pakistan 16.5%, Iran at 15.1%, Qatar 13.6%, Kuwait 8.7%, and the United Arab Emirates at 6.1%.

The African region reported 2500 new cases (2.7% of the global newly reported cases) and 38 deaths (0.9%). South Africa reported 46.4% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Algeria at 7.9%, Nigeria 13.5%, Guinea-Bissau at 3.1%, Zambia at 3.0, and Guinea at 2.8%.

The Western Pacific region reported 969 new cases (1.0% of the global newly reported cases) and 13 deaths (0.3%). Singapore reported 70.4% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines 21.5% and Malaysia 2.3%. Removing Singapore from the denominator has the Philippines at 72.5%, Malaysia at 7.7%, Japan at 7.0%, South Korea at 5.2%, and Australia at 3.1%.

The South-East Asia region reported 7062 new cases (7.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 231 deaths (5.2%). India reported 74.2% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh 18.0% and Indonesia 6.9%. These 3 countries make up 99.2% of all reported cases in the region. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 69.9% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia 26.9%, and Sri Lanka 1.2%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 18 May 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. Europe has significantly decreased. The Americas is increasing, as is South-East Asia and the Eastern Mediterranean.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkins' CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the Johns Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
